#compdef scrapscript scrapscript.com scrapscript.py
# =============================================================================
# scrapscript — tekknolagi/scrapscript's
#   reference interpreter + experimental
#   C-codegen compiler for SCRAPSCRIPT — a
#   FUNCTIONAL, CONTENT-ADDRESSABLE
#   programming language by Taylor Troesh +
#   Max Bernstein.  Every named "scrap" is
#   identified by the SHA-256 HASH of its
#   serialised syntax tree, so two scraps
#   with identical structure share the same
#   identity regardless of where or when
#   they were written.  Inspired by
#   Unison's content-addressed runtime but
#   with a smaller, ML-influenced surface
#   syntax + Haskell-style pattern matching
#   + first-class records + algebraic data
#   types.  Pure Python interpreter
#   (`scrapscript.py`) doubles as the
#   experimental C-codegen compiler for
#   producing native ELF binaries,
#   Cosmopolitan multi-platform .com
#   binaries, OR WASI Wasm modules.  134th
#   language entry in the corpus.
#
# 134TH LANGUAGE ENTRY — Scrapscript closes
# the 3+1 micro-cycle started after Axis 54
# (Apache Arrow Columnar Format) closed at
# 1/1/1 three-language symmetry in R807 (TS-
# Node=109 `_perspective` on apache-arrow
# via @perspective-dev/client + R806 Go=109
# `_gigapi` on apache/arrow-go/v18 + R805
# Rust=109 `_csv2arrow` on arrow 58.1).
#
# Distinguishing Scrapscript from the 133
# prior corpus languages — closest
# neighbours and their differences:
#   - UNISON (`_ucm`): the canonical
#     content-addressable language.
#     Differences:
#       * Unison is a FULL DISTRIBUTED
#         RUNTIME with built-in Cloud +
#         remote execution.  Scrapscript
#         is interpreted locally; the
#         `yard` HTTP server is the
#         distribution layer
#       * Unison has ability-based
#         effect tracking.  Scrapscript
#         doesn't (yet) — pure functions
#         only
#       * Unison's binary representation
#         is a tagged ABT (abstract
#         binding tree).  Scrapscript's
#         is a custom flat serialiser
#         (`flat` subcommand)
#       * Both use SHA-based content
#         hashing for identity
#   - HASKELL (`_ghc`, `_runghc`): same
#     ML/Hindley-Milner type-inference
#     lineage.  Haskell is LAZY +
#     STATICALLY TYPED with mandatory
#     types; Scrapscript is EAGER + has
#     OPTIONAL bidirectional type
#     inference via the `check`
#     subcommand
#   - OCAML (`_ocaml`, `_ocamlfind`): also
#     eager + ML-flavoured.  OCaml has
#     a full module system; Scrapscript
#     has CONTENT-ADDRESSING instead
#   - ROC (R529, `_roc`): also pure +
#     functional + ML-syntax.  Roc is
#     compile-to-native first;
#     Scrapscript is interpret-first
#     with optional compile
#   - LAWVERE (R800, `_bill`): point-
#     free categorical.  Scrapscript is
#     applicative with named arguments
#   - HASKELL-IN-FILES vs SCRAPSCRIPT-
#     CONTENT-ADDRESSED: in a Haskell
#     codebase, refactoring requires
#     manual import-path updates across
#     all consumers.  In Scrapscript,
#     the hash IS the identity — once
#     defined, a scrap can be referenced
#     by `$sha256hash` from anywhere
#
# KEY SCRAPSCRIPT LANGUAGE FEATURES:
#   - CONTENT-ADDRESSED IDENTITY — every
#     scrap is serialised to a flat
#     binary form, hashed with SHA-256,
#     and addressable globally by that
#     hash.  Refactoring is renaming
#     without breaking consumers
#   - PATTERN MATCHING — Haskell-style
#     `match {pattern -> expr | ...}`
#     destructuring on records, tuples,
#     sum types
#   - FIRST-CLASS RECORDS — `{x = 1, y =
#     2}` literal syntax; structural
#     subtyping (not nominal)
#   - SUM TYPES — `#tag value`
#     constructors; pattern-match to
#     destructure
#   - LAMBDAS WITH IMPLICIT CURRY —
#     `x -> y -> x + y` is the curried
#     adder
#   - LET BINDINGS — `let x = 5; expr`
#     for local definitions
#   - LIST + STRING LITERALS — `[1, 2,
#     3]` and `"hello"`
#   - PIPE OPERATOR — `expr |> fn` for
#     left-to-right application (like
#     Elm, F#)
#   - WHERE CLAUSES — `expr where (x =
#     5; y = 6)` post-defines locals
#   - HINDLEY-MILNER TYPE INFERENCE —
#     OPTIONAL via `scrapscript check`;
#     runtime is dynamically typed by
#     default
#   - HASH REFERENCES — `$<sha>` in
#     source code references a scrap
#     by its hash; the `yard server`
#     resolves these at load time
#
# CLI ARGUMENT PARSER — Python `argparse`
# with subparsers.  All subcommands take
# `--debug` as an option (enables debug
# logging at the boot path)
#
# SUBCOMMANDS:
#   * `repl`            interactive REPL
#                       with readline
#                       (`code.InteractiveCon
#                       sole` based);
#                       supports `--debug`
#   * `eval FILE`       evaluate a `.scrap`
#                       file and print
#                       the result
#   * `check FILE`      run Hindley-Milner
#                       type inference on
#                       a `.scrap` file
#                       and print the
#                       inferred type
#   * `apply STR`       evaluate a string
#                       literal expression
#                       directly (no file)
#   * `compile FILE`    compile a `.scrap`
#                       file to C source
#                       (default
#                       `output.c`).
#                       Flags:
#                       -o / --output;
#                       --format (clang-
#                       format the output);
#                       --compile (also
#                       invoke cc to
#                       produce a.out);
#                       --run (compile +
#                       execute);
#                       --check (type-
#                       check before
#                       compile);
#                       --memory <N>
#                       (heap size in
#                       bytes);
#                       --handle-stack-
#                       size <N>;
#                       --platform (C
#                       platform shim,
#                       default ./cli.c);
#                       --debug
#   * `flat`            serialise a
#                       scrapscript
#                       program (read from
#                       stdin) to its
#                       flat binary
#                       representation
#                       on stdout
#   * `yard server [DIRECTORY]`
#                       host a content-
#                       addressed scrap
#                       repository over
#                       HTTP.  Walks the
#                       directory, hashes
#                       every `.scrap`
#                       file, exposes them
#                       at `/$<hash>`
#                       endpoints.  Flags:
#                       --host (default
#                       127.0.0.1),
#                       --port (default
#                       8080)
#
# COMPILE TARGETS (selected via `CC`
# environment variable + flags):
#   * Normal ELF        `./scrapscript.py
#                       compile some.scrap`
#                       → output.c +
#                       `--compile` →
#                       a.out
#   * Cosmopolitan      `CC=cosmocc
#     (multi-platform     ./scrapscript.py
#     polyglot binary)    compile some.scrap
#                       --compile` →
#                       cross-platform
#                       a.out runnable on
#                       Linux, macOS,
#                       FreeBSD, Windows
#                       from the same
#                       binary
#   * Wasm              `CC=/opt/wasi-
#                       sdk/bin/clang
#                       CFLAGS=-D_WASI_
#                       EMULATED_MMAN
#                       LDFLAGS=-lwasi-
#                       emulated-mman
#                       ./scrapscript.py
#                       compile some.scrap
#                       --compile` →
#                       WASI-targeted
#                       Wasm module
#
# CRITICAL DEPENDENCIES:
#   - Python 3.8+              — interpreter
#                                runtime
#                                (pyproject.
#                                toml
#                                supports
#                                3.8 / 3.9
#                                / 3.10 /
#                                3.11)
#   - readline (optional)      — Python
#                                stdlib for
#                                REPL line
#                                editing
#   - clang or any C99         — for
#                                `--compile`
#                                step
#                                (CC env var
#                                overridable)
#   - Cosmopolitan cosmocc     — optional,
#                                for multi-
#                                platform
#                                binary
#                                builds
#   - WASI SDK clang           — optional,
#                                for Wasm
#                                output
#   - clang-format-15          — optional,
#                                for
#                                `--format`
#
# Single-file pure-Python implementation
# in `scrapscript.py` (>3000 LOC).  No
# external Python dependencies at runtime
# (`mypy`, `ruff`, `pylint` are dev-only)
#
# UPSTREAM:
#   * Source             : https://github.com/tekknolagi/scrapscript
#   * Site               : https://scrapscript.org
#   * Docker             : ghcr.io/tekknolagi/scrapscript:trunk
#   * Cosmopolitan       : https://justine.lol/cosmopolitan/
#   * License            : MIT
#   * Authors            : Max Bernstein <python@bernsteinbear.com>,
#                          Chris Gregory <christopher.b.gregory@gmail.com>
#
# INSTALL:
#   # Clone + use directly
#   git clone https://github.com/tekknolagi/scrapscript
#   cd scrapscript
#   python3 scrapscript.py repl
#
#   # Build the Cosmopolitan polyglot
#   # binary
#   ./util/build-com
#   ./scrapscript.com repl
#
#   # Docker
#   docker run --mount type=bind,source="$(pwd)",target=/mnt \
#       -i -t ghcr.io/tekknolagi/scrapscript:trunk \
#       eval /mnt/examples/0_home/factorial.scrap
#
# USAGE EXAMPLES:
#
#   # Interactive REPL
#   scrapscript repl
#
#   # Evaluate a file
#   scrapscript eval examples/0_home/factorial.scrap
#
#   # Type-check a file
#   scrapscript check examples/0_home/factorial.scrap
#
#   # Evaluate an inline expression
#   scrapscript apply "1 + 2"
#   scrapscript apply 'let x = 5; x * x'
#
#   # Compile to C source (default output.c)
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap
#
#   # Compile to C + native binary
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap --compile
#
#   # Compile + execute in one step
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap --run
#
#   # Compile with type-check first (fail
#   # fast on type errors)
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap --check
#
#   # Custom output path + clang-formatted
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap \
#       -o build/my.c --format
#
#   # Tune heap size (bytes)
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap --memory 16777216 --compile
#
#   # Tune handle-stack size
#   scrapscript compile my.scrap \
#       --handle-stack-size 1024 --compile
#
#   # Use Cosmopolitan cosmocc for cross-
#   # platform binary
#   CC=~/Downloads/cosmos/bin/cosmocc \
#       scrapscript compile my.scrap --compile
#
#   # Use WASI SDK for Wasm output
#   CC=/opt/wasi-sdk/bin/clang \
#   CFLAGS=-D_WASI_EMULATED_MMAN \
#   LDFLAGS=-lwasi-emulated-mman \
#       scrapscript compile my.scrap --compile
#
#   # Serialise a program from stdin to
#   # flat binary on stdout
#   echo '1 + 2' | scrapscript flat > program.bin
#
#   # Host a content-addressed scrap
#   # repository on http://127.0.0.1:8080
#   scrapscript yard server ./my-scraps
#
#   # Custom host + port for the yard
#   scrapscript yard server ./my-scraps \
#       --host 0.0.0.0 --port 4321
#
#   # Debug logging
#   scrapscript eval my.scrap --debug
#
#   # Help (argparse default)
#   scrapscript --help
#   scrapscript eval --help
#   scrapscript compile --help
#
# OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/tekknolagi/scrapscript/blob/trunk/scrapscript.py main()):
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _scrap_commands
_scrap_commands=(
    'repl:Interactive REPL with readline'
    'eval:Evaluate a .scrap file and print the result'
    'check:Run Hindley-Milner type inference on a .scrap file'
    'apply:Evaluate a string-literal expression directly (no file)'
    'compile:Compile a .scrap file to C source (and optionally native binary)'
    'flat:Serialise stdin scrapscript program to flat binary on stdout'
    'yard:Content-addressed scrap repository operations'
)

local -a _scrap_yard_actions
_scrap_yard_actions=(
    'server:Host a content-addressed scrap repository over HTTP'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(-): :->command' \
    '(-)*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    command)
        _describe -t commands 'scrapscript command' _scrap_commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $line[1] in
            repl)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for repl]' \
                    '--debug[enable debug logging at boot]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            eval|check)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for this subcommand]' \
                    '--debug[enable debug logging at boot]' \
                    '1:Scrapscript source file:_files -g "*.scrap"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            apply)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for apply]' \
                    '--debug[enable debug logging at boot]' \
                    '1:Scrapscript expression string:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            compile)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for compile]' \
                    '(-o --output)'{-o+,--output=}'[output C file (default output.c)]:file:_files -g "*.c"' \
                    '--format[run clang-format-15 on the generated C output]' \
                    '--compile[also invoke $CC to produce a native binary]' \
                    '--memory=[heap size in bytes]:bytes: ' \
                    '--handle-stack-size=[handle stack size]:n: ' \
                    '--run[compile + execute the resulting binary in one step]' \
                    '--check[run Hindley-Milner type inference before compile]' \
                    '--platform=[C platform shim file (default ./cli.c)]:file:_files -g "*.c"' \
                    '--debug[enable debug logging at boot]' \
                    '1:Scrapscript source file:_files -g "*.scrap"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            flat)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for flat]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            yard)
                _arguments -C \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for yard]' \
                    '1::action:->yaction' \
                    '*:: :->yargs' \
                    && ret=0
                case $state in
                    yaction)
                        _describe -t actions 'yard action' _scrap_yard_actions && ret=0 ;;
                    yargs)
                        case $line[1] in
                            server)
                                _arguments \
                                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help for yard server]' \
                                    '--host=[bind host (default 127.0.0.1)]:host: ' \
                                    '--port=[bind port (default 8080)]:port: ' \
                                    '1::directory:_files -/' \
                                    && ret=0 ;;
                        esac
                        ;;
                esac
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
